value.value: The extent to which a measurement method accurately represents a construct and is able to produce an observation distinct from that produced by a measure of another construct.
Extent to which the measurement correlates with an external criterion of the phenomenon under study.
Blockage of the uterine outlet. Causes include uterine tumors and adhesions.
A painful sensation in the uterus.

label.value: Colorectal Cancer pT4a TNM Finding v6

value.value: Colorectal cancer which directly invades other organs or structures.

label.value: Colorectal Cancer pT4b TNM Finding v6

value.value: Colorectal cancer which penetrates the visceral peritoneum.
Congenital or acquired narrowing of the lumen of the uterine cervix.
Leakage due to breakdown of a vaginal anastomosis.

An uncomfortable feeling of itching and burning in the vaginal opening resulting from inadequate vaginal lubrication. It is commonly seen during and after menopause, childbirth, or stressful conditions. It results in painful intercourse.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces alboniger.  Acting as an analog of the 3' terminal end of aminoacyl-tRNA, puromycin incorporates itself into a growing polypeptide chain and causes its premature termination, thereby inhibiting protein synthesis.  This agent has antimicrobial, antitrypanosomal, and antineoplastic properties; it is used as an antibiotic in cell culture. (NCI04)
A carcinoma of the penis that reappears after a period of remission.
Congenital or acquired blockage of the vagina.
A painful sensation in the vagina.
A rupture in the vaginal wall due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

Tightness of the vaginal wall during vaginal penetration including sexual intercourse. It is caused by involuntary spasm of the pelvic floor muscles, and results in painful intercourse or failure to have intercourse. It may due to psychological conditions, trauma in the vaginal area, or vaginal infection.
Leakage due to breakdown of a vas deferens anastomosis.
Bleeding originating from the vas deferens.
Blockage of the normal flow of the sperm in the vas deferens.
A rupture in the wall of the vas deferens.
Narrowing of the lumen of the vas deferens.

Complications related to damage at the vascular access site. Examples include bleeding, formation of hematoma, aneurysm, pseudoaneurysm, or arteriovenous fistula, development of infection, and catheter thrombosis.
A B-or T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of a mixed-sized lymphocytic population occurring in adults.
An infectious process originating from an implanted vascular device.
Damage to a vein from traumatic or pathologic processes.

Decreased blood supply to the small or large intestine due to narrowing or blockage of a visceral (mesenteric) artery. The ischemia results to the damage of the intestinal tissues. It may be chronic, caused by atherosclerosis or acute, secondary to the formation of a thrombus or embolus in the mesenteric arterial lumen. In chronic ischemia, patients present with abdominal pain manifested in a short time after a meal and weight loss. In acute ischemia, patients present with sudden and acute abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting, and blood in the stool.
A group of animals of the same species that are living, or being housed together.
Accumulation of an excessive amount of watery fluid in the visceral tissues. Symptoms include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.
A pulmonary function test result indicating an abnormal vital capacity as compared to the predicted value.
An infectious process affecting the vulva. Causative agents include human papillomavirus, herpes virus, Trichomonas, and Candida. Symptoms include itching and pain in the genital area and discharge.

Excessive tearing of the eyes due to either tear overproduction or impaired drainage of the tear ducts. Causes of tear overproduction include eye irritation (e.g., eye infection, foreign body in the eye), headache, pain reaction, allergies, sinusitis, and injury to the eye.

A symptom and a finding during physical examination, characterized by a high-pitched, whistling sound during breathing. It results from the narrowing or obstruction of the respiratory airways. The most common causes of wheezing are asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, tracheobronchitis, and pulmonary edema.
A medical condition that develops at the site of an existing wound. Examples include swelling, draining, bleeding, formation of hematoma, infection, and necrosis.
A B-or T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of a diffuse large cell lymphocytic infiltrate occurring in adults.
An individual qualified to perform an evaluation who is masked from a subject's data in order to minimize bias or maximize consistency and quality.
The quantity of a product that has been dispensed.
The quantity of a product that has been returned.
A specimen that has undergone calcification.
A specimen that has become coagulated.
A specimen that has undergone autolysis, or self-digestion by the specimen's own digestive enzymes.
An external committee whose purpose is to evaluate study data and decide whether a study endpoint or other criterion has been met.
Reported values within the typical or expected range.
An indefinite large quantity that is considered to be greater than several.

Blood found in arteries, generally oxygenated blood which is transported with nutrients to body tissues through the arterial system. The exception is blood within the pulmonary artery which carries deoxygenated blood to the lungs.
A morphologic variant of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma occurring in adults.  It is characterized by the presence of large lymphoid cells with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli.

Blood carried in veins, generally deoxygenated blood containing urea and other waste products which is transported through the venous system to the heart and lungs. The exception is blood within the pulmonary vein which is oxygenated and travels from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart.
